						               													<description>Postcard Brittany is a relatively fast and simple - NO &amp;quot;Zones of Control!&amp;quot; - but historical little 6-turn sudden-death game about General George Patton's August 1944 coup de main attempts to grab the major French ports of Brittany, before the Germans could organize their defenses.&amp;#10;Regimental level: 14 German units, 3 French FFI groups, and 11 US units in hex-and-counter format.&amp;#10;1-4 player game with at least initially hidden German units spread out in the peninsula.&amp;#10;Allied movement impeded by Strassesperren - roadblocks - as well as German units ... as well as traffic jamming on roads.&amp;#10;FFI groups can recon unknown German units, destroy undefended German roadblocks, and block German retreats.&amp;#10;Patton's special engineer-equipped Task Force A included, and it can be 'decisive.'  (Thanks, George.)&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Historically, Patton failed, chafing at the corps commander's hesitancy, but you can do better. Right? :-)&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Good solitaire game - or in very large format, team game - with US 4th and 6th Armored Divisions necessarily going down separate east-west roads.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;mdash;description from the designer&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
